Data sets

We are going use three datasets in this project. These datasets will cover the period before the election (approval rate data), period during the election (US Election 2020 Tweets), and last dataset for the actual election results (1976-2020-president). The following section will elaborate more on these dataseta and the main role for each one.

US Election 2020 Tweets

The “U.S. election 2020 Tweets” is the main dataset for this project. The dataset contains Tweets collected using Twitter API during the most critical period in the presidency election race. Tweets are splited into 2 CSV files. The first file contains all tweets with hastag related to election and Donald Trump while the other one contains tweets with hashtag for Joe Biden. Both files cover the period from 15th-Oct 2020 to 8th-Nov-2020. Dataset contains many other useful information beside tweet text as number of like, number of retweets, user location (continent, country, state…etc.), user name on tweeter and some other useful information. The following paragraph will share some statisctics on this data sets.

Dataset name: US Election 2020 Tweets Description: Tweets collected, using the Twitter API statuses_lookup and snsscrape during the election period. The dataset contains 2 files, one of the former president “Donald Trump” and the other one for tweets related to the current president “Joe Biden”.

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/manchunhui/us-election-2020-tweets Type: CSV Size: 0.8 GB Number of files: 2 Number of variables: 21 Number of observations: ~ 2 M records Suggested database: Although the tweets are unstructured data in nature, but the data stored in CSV tabular format, so we can store it in any database. Relational DB, Graph database, or NoSQL database Key Columns: The following attributes will be as the reference columns that can be used to join this dataset with the other two datasets that we rae going to use in this project (approval rate data) and (XXXXXXXX)

Let’s examine the Country distinct values to make sure that we done’t have data quality issues in that column.

unique(filter(Biden.Trump.merged, substr(Biden.Trump.merged$country,1,6) == "United")$country)
## [1] "United States of America" "United Kingdom"          
## [3] "United States"            "United Arab Emirates"

We can see that we have a data quality issue here as United States stored in the dataset using two different values + United States of America + United States To fix that we will replace “United States of America” values with “United States” value.

Biden.Trump.merged$country[Biden.Trump.merged$country == "United States of America"] <- "United States"

Now, we have only one value to represent “United States”

unique(filter(Biden.Trump.merged, substr(Biden.Trump.merged$country,1,6) == "United")$country)
## [1] "United States"        "United Kingdom"       "United Arab Emirates"
